community and to the Chinese across the Pacific, his posthumous journey through translation, and China's reception of the author and his work, Mark Twain in China points to the repercussions of Twain in a global theater. It highlights the cultural specificity of concepts such as "race," "nation," and "empire," and helps us rethink their alternative legacies in countries with dramatically different racial and cultural dynamics from the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChinese Americans in literature. 0aRace relations in literature. 4aChina. 4aHuckleberry Finn. 4aMark Twain. 4aPacific. 4aUnited States. 4aadventures. 4aculture. 4aglobal. 4arace. 4atranslation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804794756zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804794756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804794756.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles